{"cursor":"17891","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\nIn the writings of Karl Marx and the Marxist theory of historical materialism, a\n'mode of production' (in German: Produktionsweise, meaning 'the way of\nproducing') is a specific combination of:\n\n*productive forces: these include human labour power and available knowledge\ngiven the level of technology in the means of production (e.g. tools, equipment,\nbuildings and technologies, materials, and improved land). *social and technical\nrelations of production: these include the property, power, and control\nrelations governing society's productive assets (often codified in law,\ncooperative work relations, and forms of association), relations between people\nand the objects of their work, and the relations between social classes.\n\nMarx regarded productive ability and participation in social relations as two\nessential characteristics of human beings and that the particular modality of\nthese relations in capitalist production are inherently in conflict with the\nincreasing development of human productive capacities. [http://www.marxists-\n.org/archive/marx/works/1857/grundrisse/ch11.htm#p594 Marx, Grundrisse. (English\nTranslation)]\n","linknr":460,"url":"Mode_of_production","recorded":1362552157,"links":28,"instances":["marxian","project_management","economics","marxism","intentional_community","polity"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Marxist terminology","Theories of history","Economic systems|","Marxism","Political economy","Sociological terminology"],"headings":["Significance of concept","The modes of production in history","Articulation of modes of production","See also","Notes","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/79/Marx_and_Engels.jpg/180px-Marx_and_Engels.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c5/Red_flag_waving.svg/15px-Red_flag_waving.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/fd/Portal-puzzle.svg/16px-Portal-puzzle.svg.png","/